Happy to help design this! Here's a clean REST API structure:

## Resources

```
GET    /api/users/{id}
POST   /api/users

GET    /api/projects
POST   /api/projects
GET    /api/projects/{id}
PUT    /api/projects/{id}
DELETE /api/projects/{id}

GET    /api/projects/{id}/tasks
POST   /api/projects/{id}/tasks
GET    /api/tasks/{id}
PUT    /api/tasks/{id}
PATCH  /api/tasks/{id}
DELETE /api/tasks/{id}
```

## Task schema

```json
{
  "id": "task_abc123",
  "title": "Write API documentation",
  "description": "Document all endpoints with examples",
  "status": "in_progress",
  "priority": "high",
  "project_id": "proj_xyz",
  "assignee_id": "user_123",
  "due_date": "2024-06-15T23:59:59Z",
  "created_at": "2024-06-01T09:00:00Z",
  "updated_at": "2024-06-01T09:00:00Z"
}
```

## Key decisions

**Use PATCH for partial updates** — `PUT` replaces the entire resource, `PATCH` updates only the fields you send. For tasks you'll mostly want PATCH (toggle status, update title, etc.).

**Nest tasks under projects** for listing — `/api/projects/{id}/tasks` makes it easy to get all tasks in a project. But `/api/tasks/{id}` for individual task operations keeps URLs short.

**Consistent error format:**
```json
{
  "error": {
    "code": "TASK_NOT_FOUND",
    "message": "Task task_abc123 not found",
    "status": 404
  }
}
```

